firstComment: In late winter this year a squirrel made its home in my bedroom wall. At first I was aggravated and annoyed, but really it was just a triggering experience for me. Fortunately I‚Äôve been on the healing/discovery/integration journey for a while now and I quickly saw it as an opportunity to do just that, Heal, discover, integrate. Life is always sending us the tools(situations/circumstances) we need so that we can let go of what no longer serves us. I equated the stirring sounds I‚Äôd occasionally hear as intrusive thoughts.. and it was less about my intrusive thoughts not serving me, and more about the way I was judging them. That is what caused me suffering. If only there was a way for me to stay pleasant and present when the intrusive thought clouds are passing through‚Ä¶ enter the wall squirrel ‚ú®üêøÔ∏è‚ú® I flipped the script inside my head. I did my best to show my squirrel friend patience and understanding. I named them ‚ÄúWally‚Äù and before I knew it, the sounds I once found triggering became comforting, loving, and comical. My roommate and I watch movies in my room with my projector, and where we‚Äôd sit on my couch placed Wally‚Äôs wall nook right between our heads. We‚Äôd be absorbed in what we were watching and then hear Wally scratch a little or make a cute sound and all we could do is look at each other and laugh. At one point I was told I should inform my landlord because of the damage Wally could cause. I got worried by the idea that an exterminator might have to get involved. So I banged on the wall and told Wally to move out. I heard little squeaks answer back üòÆ it had to be a baby! Luckily my landlord didn‚Äôt want to interveneüôèüèºüôÑFast forward to now and Wally and her baby have moved out and I‚Äôve earned her trust enough that I am able to hand feed her! This is the first wild animal I‚Äôve had this kind of a connection with. I think it really helped that she got comfortable with my voice while she stayed in the wall. She brings lots of joy to me and my roomies. I‚Äôm very grateful for her and the opportunity to develop more self compassion that she brought into my life. Thank you for this post, and thank you for reading(:
